Succulent @shrimp{10%ounce}, sweet @poblano pepper{1}, and tangy @green olives{1%ounce} are finished
with a burst of citrus in this quick #skillet{} sauté. The sauce uses a combo of @orange{1} and @lemon{1}
juices and zests to keep things bright and sunshine-y. Plain @basmati rice{1/2%cup} is all that's needed
to accompany it on the plate—the grains do a great job of soaking up all those vibrant flavors.

Wash and dry all produce. Bring @water{1%cup} and @salt{pinch} to a boil in a #small pot{}. Once boiling,
add rice, cover, and reduce to a simmer. Cook until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Remove from heat and keep covered.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @red onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Halve @poblano pepper{1} lengthwise and
remove the core and white ribs. Cut crosswise into thin strips. Thinly slice @garlic{2%clove}(thinly sliced)
and @green olives{1%ounce}(thinly sliced). Zest, halve, and juice @orange{1}(zested, halved, and juiced) and
@lemon{1}(zested, halved, and juiced) into a #small bowl{}. Pick @oregano{1/4%ounce}(leaves picked from stems
and roughly chopped). Discard stems.

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add poblano and onion and cook until softened
and slightly charred, about ~{5%minutes}, tossing occasionally.

Add garlic, olives, oregano, and half the citrus juice to pan. Reduce heat to medium and cook until fragrant,
~{2-3%minutes}, tossing.

Season shrimp with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Add to pan with @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Cook until pink and
just firm, about ~{3-5%minutes}, tossing occasionally. Pour in remaining juice, along with @orange zest{1%tsp}
and @lemon zest{1%tsp}. Toss and season with salt and pepper.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}. Season to taste with salt, pepper, and remaining citrus zest. Divide rice between
plates and top with shrimp and its sauce.